ce:section.ce:para:
The advanced oxidation processes (AOPs) were first proposed in 1987 by Glaze [12], and they are widely used for wastewater treatment via the in-suit generation of a variety of powerful oxidizing hydroxyl radicals (HO•) to degrade the organic pollutants. In this work, the O3/H2O2/UV process, one of the most effective processes of AOPs type for wastewater treatment, is employed to prepare the GQDs. Corporate with UV and hydrogen peroxide, the ozone can react with water to generated a large number of HO• [13,14]. In the process, the 254 nm and 180 nm photons were emitted generally from a low pressure mercury lamp, the 254 nm photons can accelerate the decomposition of hydrogen peroxide into hydroxyl radicals. Meanwhile, the oxygen could be converted into ozone under the 180 nm photons irradiation to further accelerate the generation rate of HO• [15]. Hydroxyl radicals are the most reactive oxygen species and can react effectively with GO, and which quickly and efficiently fragments the GO sheets into GQDs. The AFM and TEM were used to monitor the reaction process of GO as it was cut into GQDs (Fig. 1
                     , Fig. 2
                     ). A few holes emerged on the basal plane of GO sheets after 0.5 h of reaction (Fig. 2a). The pore size increased with the increased reaction time (Fig. 1b, Fig. 2b). Fig. 1c shows that after 2 h of reaction, the GO sheets were cut into small pieces. For the sample reacting after 3 h, all the GO sheets were fragmented into the GQDs with an average lateral size of 2.16 nm (Fig. 2c, Fig. 2d, and Fig. 2e). In particular, Fig. 2c shows how the high resolution TEM image indicates that the GQDs (as generated) have a high crystalline structure with a lattice parameter of ~0.203 nm, which corresponds to that of (100) graphene planes[16]. After filtration and freeze drying, the GQDs powders were obtained and the production yield was about 48% in weight. It was difficult to remove inorganic salts and acids in the advanced oxidation methods for the synthesis of GQDs reported previously, which is time- and cost-consuming [17-19]. Obviously, the improved AOP-driven stripping strategy for synthesizing GQDs in this work is efficient, low cost, and environmentally friendly.
